properties.description: Accuracy is a must on this opening tee shot so choose your cub wisely. Approach is to a green tightly guarded by bunkers on the left and trees everywhere else.
Straight forward par 3 to large green. May need to club down for the downhill layout. Make up strokes that may have been lost on the 1st.
Ideal drive is right center of fairway. Long hitters will be tempted to get home in two. Be aware of the well placed bunker protecting the front, left of the green.
Straight away par 4. Using a fairway wood or hybrid is a wise play here due to the hazard crossing the fairway. Approach is to a small, undulating green.
Grip it and rip it to carry the hazard. Long par 4 leads to an approach to a narrow green sloping back to front.
If you do not carry the bunkers in the center of the fairway, staying left of them is the best angle to the pin on this short par 4.
Intimidating tee shot, but take aim right of the Ash tree and more at the fairway bunkers and trust it. Approach is to a two-tiered green with water left.
Water and bunkers evident here, but biggest hazard is usually the wind. Bail out area is right of a large, receptive green.

Favor the right side of the fairway here for obvious reasons. Getting home in two here is quite a task. Best play is a safe lay-up leading to a two-tiered green that is protected by sand right and water left.
Traditional straight-away par 4 leading to a small green severely sloped back to front.
Ideal drive on this longer par 4 is on top of the hill for an approach to a wide, but shallow green. Gully on right makes for a tough chip.
What you see is what you get. Well protected green and going long also leaves a difficult chip back. This hole makes you fight for that birdie or par!
The challenge here is to stay out of the numerous bunkers landscaping this entire hole. Choose your path wisely and a par or birdie can be made on this long par 5 to an elevated green.
Long, straight par 4 with large accepting fairway. Short, right is the best angle for a chip if your approach shot misses.

Water lurks throughout this par 5. Hit your tee shot left of the bunker. Smart play is to lay up short of the water separating the green from the fairway. Then stick your short iron to an accepting green.
Trees on the right have a big appetite for golf balls, so think left side of the fairway here. Small, flat green is well protected by trees and bunker on the right.
Trouble surrounds this longer par 3 so stand firm. The green is the goal but a short, straight tee shot is the next best result. A par hereâ€¦take your bow.
Terrific finishing hole. Ideally keep your drive on the right side of the fairway for a clear shot to an open but elevated green.
